I work for IBM (in a different division) but believe me, a lot of
us do wonder why a technically superior product is having such a hard
time catching on.

Yes, Bill Gates owns the software industry, not just for PCs but for
Macs as well.  Windows & it's related products might be unstable and
inferior, but they have a *much* larger installed base.  There are
like 50 million copies of Windows in existence vs. 5 million copies
of OS/2.  This leads to two problems:

  [1] If you were a software developer, which market are you going to
      pay attention to ?

  [2] If you were a computer manufacturer, what are you going to
      package with your system ?


And then there is the customer side of things; people have large
investments in Windows software that they are not going to risk.
Yes, OS/2 does Windows, but it's not native and not perfect.

Things you can do about this:

  [1] Buy OS/2 native versions of software; don't put up with running
      a Windows version.
  [2] If your dealer doesn't stock OS/2 & related products, find one
      that does.
  [3] Become a member of Team OS/2, or at least be one in spirit if you
      don't want your name on some list.  (I am not a member.  I don't
      consider myself knowledgeable enough yet to be of any help.)



